Titanic: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

In this project, we will perform exploratory data analysis (EDA) on a titanic shipwreck and passenger survival data. You can find the dataset files used in the Datasets folder of this repository or download them directly from the source link.

Note: While exploring datasets for this assignment, I came across the Titanic dataset on Kaggle and found it really interesting. Kaggle features this dataset as a challenge, encouraging users to analyze passenger data from the Titanic shipwreck and predict survival probabilities. I never imagined working on something like this before, so this experience was truly exciting!

Source:
Titanic - Machine Learning from Disaster
https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/titanic

Setting up the Environment¶

In the following steps, we will ensure that the project workspace is equipped with the necessary tools for data manipulation, visualization, and statistical analysis.

from tqdm.auto import tqdm

Loading the Titanic Dataset¶

In this step, we are loading a dataset containing information about the passengers who were aboard the Titanic before it sank. The dataset includes details such as passenger ID, name, age, sex, and whether they survived the disaster. It also has information on family relations, including the number of siblings or spouses they were traveling with, as well as travel details such as ticket class, ticket number, fare, cabin, and port of embarkation. Understanding the structure of this dataset will help us perform meaningful exploratory data analysis later on.

In [4]:
df_titanic = pd.read_csv('Datasets/train.csv')

Data Familiarization¶

In this section, we will perform an initial exploration of the titanic dataset.

Our goals are to:

  • Identify data types: Understand what kind of data each column holds (e.g., numerical, categorical).
  • Detect missing values: Find any absent data points that might need handling.
  • Count entries: Check the total number of rows to gauge the dataset's size.
  • Examine ranges: Look at the minimum and maximum values for numerical columns.
  • Sample entries: Display a few rows to visually inspect the data.
  • Review unique values: For categorical variables, list unique values to understand the diversity in the data.

These steps are crucial to ensure data quality before moving forward with deeper analyses.

Columns in the Titanic Dataset¶

A brief description of what each column in the dataset means.

  1. PassengerId: A unique ID assigned to each passenger in the dataset.
  2. Age: The passenger's age in years.
  3. Fare: The amount the passenger paid for their ticket (numeric).
  4. Survived: Whether the passenger survived the disaster (1 = survived, 0 = did not survive).
  5. Pclass: The socieconomic class of the passenger (1st, 2nd, or 3rd class).
  6. Sex: The passenger's gender (Male or Female).
  7. SibSp: Number of siblings or spouses the passenger was traveling with.
  8. Parch: Number of parents or children the passenger was traveling with.
  9. Embarked: The port where the passenger boarded (C = Cherbourg, Q = Queenstown, S = Southampton).
  10. Name: The full name of the passenger.
  11. Ticket: The alphanumeric ticket number assigned to the passenger.
  12. Cabin: The cabin number where the passenger stayed (many missing values).

Let's check each column separately to better understand the dataset. We can start with the 'Age' column to see the ages of the people who were on the Titanic

Identifying Column Types¶

After examining each column in our dataset, we can categorize their data types in the following way:

  • Numerical - PassengerId, Age, Fare
  • Categorical - Survived, Pclass, Sex, SibSp, Parch, Embarked
  • Mixed - Name, Ticket, Cabin

Let’s move on to performing some univariate analysis and focus on analyzing each feature in the dataset independently, at first.

Univariate Analysis¶

We begin with a fundamental statistical analysis by examining individual variables independently. At this stage, we are not focusing on relationships between variables or cause-and-effect patterns; rather, we aim to understand the distribution, central tendency, and spread of each feature in the dataset.

In this step, we generate a comprehensive summary table of the dataset that includes the count, mean, standard deviation, and various percentiles for each numeric column. This summary gives a quick, overall snapshot of the distribution and central tendencies within the data.

Descriptive Statistics & Distribution Analysis¶

Here, we compute key statistics to summarize the dataset:

  • Mean & Median: Indicate central tendency, with the median being less affected by outliers.
  • Standard Deviation: Measures data spread around the mean.
  • Quantiles: Help understand distribution shape and detect skewness.

To complement this, we will visualize distributions using histograms, KDE plots, box plots, bar charts, and pie charts to uncover patterns like skewness, modality, and outliers.

Let's start by analyzing the distribution of 'Age', as it is an important numerical variable in our dataset.

Insights from Univariate Analysis¶

In this section, we will summarize the findings of our univariate analysis and write down all the insights we have so far.

Passenger ID

  • Don't think we need to do anything with this field - just a unique identifier.

Age

  • Many infants traveling on the Titanic and a lot of middle-aged people. There weren’t many people above 60 or 70.
  • It has (almost) normal distribution.
  • 20% of the values are missing.
  • There are some outliers above age of ~65, data looked valid though.

Fare

  • The data looks a bit skewed to the right.
  • No individual fare present. Grouped family fare is added for each passenger instead.
  • No null values

Survived

  • More than half the passengers did not survive the shipwreck!
  • No null values

Pclass

  • Looks like a lot of passengers were traveling in Pclass 3 - which was the class with cheapest ticket fare.
  • After that, more people were traveling in Pclass 1 compared to Pclass 2 - which seems a bit odd!
  • No null values

Sex

  • There were more males (~65%) on the ship than females.

Sibsp

  • Looks like a lot of passengers (around 69%) were traveling alone on the Titanic.

Parch

  • Looks like a lot of passengers (around 76%) were traveling alone on the Titanic.
  • It also looks like we can create a family size column to make sense of the family together.

Embarked

  • Most of the passengers embarked from the station S (Southampton - ~72%)
  • 2 null values

Columns I couldn't do anything with:

  • Name, ticket, cabin

Conclusions¶

In this section, we will summarize the findings of our EDA and write down all the final insights and conclusions.

After analyzing the Titanic dataset, here are the key takeaways:

  • Survival and Class (Pclass): Passengers in higher classes (1st class) were more likely to survive, as seen in both Pearson and Spearman correlations. This shows that class had a big impact on survival.
  • Age and Survival: Younger passengers were slightly more likely to survive, but the relationship isn’t very strong, so age wasn’t a major factor I think.
  • Family Size: Passengers traveling with family members were more likely to survive. This suggests that having family with you on the ship could have helped increase survival chances but only smaller family sizes.
  • Fare: Passengers who paid higher fares were more likely to survive, likely because they were in higher classes with better access to lifeboats.
  • Spearman vs Pearson: Both correlation methods gave similar results, but Spearman (which looks at the rank of data) showed a slightly stronger relationship between survival and fare, while Pearson focused more on the exact values.
  • Passenger ID: The PassengerId didn’t show any important connection with survival or other features, so it doesn’t affect the analysis.
  • Ticket: Couldn't analyze this column for now.
  • Cabin: Couldn't analyze this column for now.
  • Feature Engineering: We also created new columns for family size and family size groupings to merge siblings and parent child count in the dataset.
  • Missing data: There's some missing data in the dataset for a few columns. - we have to figure out ways to handle that, mainly for age.
